  "kind" : "article",
  "metadata" : {
    "role" : "article",
    "roleHeading" : "Article",
    "title" : "Newton’s First Law"
  },
  "primaryContentSections" : [
    {
      "content" : [
        {
          "anchor" : "Overview",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Overview",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Distinguish between conditions of static equilibrium, dynamic equilibrium and acceleration.",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Draw free body diagrams for a particle in equilibrium.",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "text" : "Apply the equations of equilibrium for a particle to solve static and dynamic equilibrium",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : "problems in engineering mechanics.",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "See ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "doc:\/\/Notes\/documentation\/Notes\/Dynamics#Newtons-First-Law",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " for some starter information.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "content" : [
            {
              "inlineContent" : [
                {
                  "text" : "Newton’s First Law: An object either remain at rest or move with constant velocity",
                  "type" : "text"
                },
                {
                  "text" : " ",
                  "type" : "text"
                },
                {
                  "text" : "as long as the net force acting on it is zero.",
                  "type" : "text"
                }
              ],
              "type" : "paragraph"
            }
          ],
          "name" : "Definition",
          "style" : "note",
          "type" : "aside"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Basically it states that if nothing is moving\/accelerating, the net translational forces are 0.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Static equilibrium is when the object is at rest, and dynamic equilibrium is when the object is",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "moving with constant velocity. ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "inlineContent" : [
                {
                  "text" : "Technically",
                  "type" : "text"
                }
              ],
              "type" : "emphasis"
            },
            {
              "text" : " they’re both the same thing because Einstein, but",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "because with engineering we deal with the air and ground, we treat them as different.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Particle-Related-Problem",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Particle Related Problem",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "An object can be represented as a particle when all forces acting on it have lines of action that",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "pass through a single point (the point does not need to be anything special, or even on the",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "object).",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "These forces are known as concurrent forces. Note that because all forces act on the point, there",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "are no moments since ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$\\perp d$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " is always zero.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Equilibrium-of-Concurrent-Forces",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Equilibrium of Concurrent Forces",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "For a particle related problem, it is in equilibrium when:",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$\\sum F_x = 0$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$\\sum F_y = 0$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$\\sum M = 0$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " (note: this is a precondition for a particle related problem)",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "In non-particle related problems, it follows the same rules. Moments apply in non-particle related",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "problems, so you should make sure that ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$\\sum M = 0$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " still holds.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Finding-the-Normal-On-a-Slope",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Finding the Normal On a Slope",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "The rules for ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "identifier" : "doc:\/\/Notes\/documentation\/Notes\/5.3-Friction",
              "isActive" : true,
              "type" : "reference"
            },
            {
              "text" : " define the friction in terms of the normal force exerted by the",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "ground on the object. This is best done by redefining a coordinate system ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$x', y'$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : "aligned to the",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "slope, then using trig to find the weight’s ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$y'$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " component. The normal contact force is equal to",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "that, but in the opposite direction.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "identifier" : "Diagram_Slope Friction",
              "type" : "image"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "In the example above, we calculate the normal force to be",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "code" : [
            "W_{y'} = W \\cdot \\cos(\\theta)",
            "R_{N} = -W_{y'}"
          ],
          "syntax" : "math",
          "type" : "codeListing"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "where",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "items" : [
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$W_{y'}$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the ",
                      "type" : "text"
                    },
                    {
                      "code" : "$y'$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " component of the object’s weight, exerted on the slope",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$R_{N}$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the normal force exerted by the slope on the object",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$W$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the weight of the object in newtons",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content" : [
                {
                  "inlineContent" : [
                    {
                      "code" : "$\\theta$",
                      "type" : "codeVoice"
                    },
                    {
                      "text" : " is the angle of the slope.",
                      "type" : "text"
                    }
                  ],
                  "type" : "paragraph"
                }
              ]
            }
          ],
          "type" : "unorderedList"
        },
        {
          "anchor" : "Impending-Motion",
          "level" : 2,
          "text" : "Impending Motion",
          "type" : "heading"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "When an object is on the verge of moving but is not yet moving, it is said to be in impending",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "motion. An object in impending motion is STILL in equilibrium, but if the target force were to be",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "increased slightly, it would start moving.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Usuaully this is used when there is friction involved, and the force opposing the motion is equal",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "to the maximum force of friction (ie. ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$F = F_{friction}$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : "). This means that if the force",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "increases, it will overcome the friction and start moving.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        },
        {
          "inlineContent" : [
            {
              "text" : "Note that the friction is in the OPPOSITE direction of impending motion. A string may need to pull",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "at tension ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$T_{1}$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " to keep an object from sliding down a slope, but needs to pull at",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$T_{2}$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " where ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "code" : "$T_{2} > T_{1}$",
              "type" : "codeVoice"
            },
            {
              "text" : " to start to move it up the slope. MAKE SURE that you treat",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : " ",
              "type" : "text"
            },
            {
              "text" : "friction as the correct direction.",
              "type" : "text"
            }
          ],
          "type" : "paragraph"
        }
      ],
      "kind" : "content"
    }
  ],
